<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-section-name" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Antiderivatives, Integrals, and the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus</title>

  <p> The derivative of a function <m>f(x)</m> is the function <m>f'(x)</m> defined by the limit <me>f'(x)=\lim_{h \rightarrow 0} \frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h}</me>, where the domain of <m>f'(x)</m> includes all values <m>x</m> in the domain of <m>f</m> for which the limit exists.    </p>


